build 2026-06-25.387  (v2.14.1)

Explode/UNNEST results page in milliseconds: store reads prune by
file_row_number instead of sorting the world.

The stall's true root, found by re-reading the on-box watchdog dump: the
wedged frame was ParquetResultStore._fetch -- paging an ALREADY
MATERIALIZED result. Unsorted pages ordered by "__rn", a SYNTHESIZED
expression (file_row_number + 1), and an ORDER BY over an expression
defeats row-group pruning: a 200-row first page planned a TopN across
EVERY row group of a multi-GB nested file -- minutes of native scan that
the first interrupt can miss. Deep UNNEST/explode results are exactly the
worst case: few rows cap-wise, enormous LIST/STRUCT columns per group.

The fix exploits what "__rn" already was: raw file_row_number IS
prunable. Unsorted paging now emits

    SELECT cols FROM read_parquet(store, file_row_number = true)
    WHERE file_row_number >= offset AND file_row_number < offset+limit
    ORDER BY file_row_number

so a page reads only the row group(s) it lands in -- same rows, same
order, tiny I/O, and trivially interruptible. Integer indexing prunes to
a single row's group; exports stream in raw file order with NO
synthesized sort planned. A USER sort keeps the legacy TopN (a genuine
reorder of the data is unavoidable). Combined with the existing 10M-row
producer cap and the .386 escalation, the explode-page-stall class is
closed: bounded write, pruned reads, re-fired cancels.

Executed tests against a recording engine pin all four SQL shapes: the
pruned unsorted page, the single-group integer index, the sort-free
export stream, and the untouched user-sort TopN.

