The actual reason flatten-on-load crawled: a quadratic JSON reader. Fixed.

Every previous round tuned the wrong thing (a faster writer, a native flatten,
Arrow inserts) because the real cost was upstream, in the streaming JSON reader
that feeds the flattener. It decoded one value at a time by re-running the
parser from the START of a growing text buffer and copying the tail after every
value (buf = buf[end:]). Both are O(n-squared) in the size of an INDIVIDUAL
record: small records were fine, but a file of large records -- the Sophis
wrappers are ~1.7 MB each -- spent almost all its time re-scanning bytes it had
already parsed. Measured here on synthetic files, read throughput collapsed as
records grew:

    record size     old reader     new reader
    77 KB           47 MB/s        69 MB/s
    1.5 MB          7.8 MB/s       59 MB/s
    4 MB            3.1 MB/s       44 MB/s

That collapse is why a multi-GB file of fat records read at kilobytes a second.

The fix: both stdlib readers now decode by advancing an INDEX into the buffer
(raw_decode at a position -- never re-slicing off the front), and when one value
runs past the end of the buffer they read a GROWING chunk (1 MB, doubling up to
16 MB) to complete it instead of nibbling 64 KB at a time and re-scanning. Read
throughput is now flat regardless of record size, and it stays fully streaming
(bounded memory) and cancellable. Every existing reader test -- concatenated
arrays/objects, NDJSON, mixed streams, NaN/Infinity, BOM, cancel-mid-read,
deep-array linkage, stream+spill equivalence -- still passes unchanged, and a new
regression test reads multi-MB concatenated records back intact and guards the
index + growing-read approach so the quadratic pattern can't return.

With the reader linear, the remaining load cost is the flattener's per-record
dict-walking (genuinely linear work) plus the Arrow bulk write from .326. On the
synthetic 1.5 MB-record file the whole read+flatten now runs at ~16 MB/s (was
~5), so the phase that was taking most of an hour on the real file should be a
few minutes. If it is still slower than you want, that is now the flatten CPU
cost, not a bug -- tell me and I will profile that next.

