build 2026-06-25.310  (v2.10.39)

Large loads now go to on-disk columnar storage instead of an in-memory table,
so memory stays bounded for the whole lifecycle -- not just while reading.

A file at or above a size threshold (512 MB by default; set SAMQL_ONDISK_MB, or
0 to turn the feature off) is now streamed into a Parquet cache and queried
through a read_parquet view, rather than materialised into an in-memory DuckDB
table. The rows never live in the engine, so a genuinely huge dataset no longer
becomes a memory-pressure point after it loads -- queries read straight from the
columnar file with column + row-group pushdown (only the columns/rows a query
needs are touched) and cached Parquet metadata for fast repeat scans, which is
the common case here (a node graph fires many queries at one source). A file
that is already Parquet is simply viewed in place (no re-copy). Smaller files
still materialise in memory, where that's fastest. If the Parquet route ever
fails for a non-cancel reason the loader falls back to the in-memory table, so
this is never worse than before. The large-JSON-array pre-pass and the
cancellation from the last builds apply on this path too.

Why Parquet and not an on-disk DuckDB database: it reuses the engine's existing,
tested Parquet-view path; it bounds memory across ingest AND queries (nothing is
materialised); Parquet is portable and version-independent, where a .duckdb file
is tied to the engine version; and object-cached metadata plus pushdown make
repeat queries fast. An on-disk DuckDB table can edge it out on some repeated
complex queries but needs attach/versioning machinery for a marginal gain. To
check the trade-off on real data there's a new tools/bench_large_load.py that
loads a file three ways -- in-memory, Parquet view, and on-disk DuckDB -- each in
its own process, and reports load time, a sample query time, and peak memory, so
the choice can be validated per machine and file.

Reasoned vs tested: the size threshold and its off switch are unit-tested and
run everywhere. The end-to-end large load landing as a Parquet cache view --
queryable, right rows and columns, backed by a Parquet file rather than an
in-memory copy -- is covered by a test that runs wherever DuckDB is installed
and skips in the sandbox. The COPY-to-Parquet-then-view path reuses the same
statements the convert-to-Parquet feature already exercises. The benchmark's
own logic (reader selection, the array pre-pass, memory measurement) is
smoke-checked here; its DuckDB runs happen on your machine. The suite is green.

