build 2026-06-25.307  (v2.10.36)

Large single JSON arrays now stream instead of running out of memory.

A JSON file that is one big top-level array -- [ {...}, {...}, ... ] -- is the
one shape DuckDB's JSON reader has to buffer essentially whole: unlike
newline-delimited JSON, it can't stream the elements or spill them, so on a
multi-GB array it exhausts the memory limit before a single row lands ("Out of
Memory Error: failed to allocate ... while reading the file"). When a load hits
a JSON file at or above a size threshold (128 MB by default; set
SAMQL_JSON_STREAM_MB to change it) and it turns out to be a single top-level
array, the loader now rewrites it to newline-delimited JSON first, in a
streaming pass that holds only a small read buffer no matter how big the file
is, and points DuckDB at that instead. DuckDB then streams it row by row and
spills to its temp directory as usual. The element split is done by the
standard library's JSON decoder, so nested objects, arrays, escaped quotes and
the like are handled exactly; the temp file is cleaned up once the table is
built. Files below the threshold, newline-delimited files, and single-object
files are untouched -- they already load fine. The resulting table shows the
object keys as columns, same as any other JSON load.

This pairs with the existing memory safeguards (the auto-sized DuckDB memory
limit, which an admin can override with SAMQL_DUCKDB_MEMORY_GB, plus spill to a
managed temp directory): the limit and spill handle big tables once they are
loaded, and this handles getting an oversized array in without blowing the
limit during the read itself.

Reasoned vs tested: the streaming converter is unit-tested directly, including
the boundary cases a naive splitter gets wrong -- a value or a number that
straddles a read-buffer boundary, strings that contain brackets/braces/commas,
escaped quotes and backslashes, a byte-order mark, and non-array inputs that
must be left alone -- run at deliberately tiny buffer sizes to force refills
everywhere. The end-to-end DuckDB load of a top-level array through this path is
covered by a test that runs wherever DuckDB is installed (it skips in the CI
sandbox, which has no DuckDB). The suite is green.

