build 2026-06-25.301  (v2.10.30)

Three improvements: deeper JSON flattening, memory-bounded API loads, and a
pivot that collapses to its subtotals.

JSON flattening now handles arrays nested three or more levels deep -- they
explode into chained child tables (parent, child, child items, ...) instead of
being stringified at the third level, so the inner values stay queryable. A
depth cap keeps a pathologically deep document from overflowing the parser
stack: past the cap a still-nested value is kept verbatim rather than crashing.
A field whose type differs between records (sometimes a scalar, sometimes an
object) stays lossless, and one- and two-level shapes are byte-for-byte
unchanged.

Loading an API response into SQLite is now memory-bounded. The records are
streamed straight from the spooled response into the flattener, which spills its
per-table row buffers to disk past a threshold, so neither the parsed records
nor the flattened rows are all held in memory at once -- the same way file loads
already work, and the way the DuckDB path already reads the file directly. A
2xx response that turns out to hold no records still gives a clean "no records"
message instead of a parser error.

In a pivot with subtotals turned on, collapsing a nested row group now shows
that group's rolled-up subtotal values on the collapsed line -- the Excel /
Tableau "collapse to subtotal" behaviour -- instead of blanking the row and
showing only a count. Expanding restores the detail rows.

Reasoned vs tested: the flattening and API-load changes are covered by new tests
(deep and mixed-type arrays plus the depth cap; a streamed-and-spilled API load
with a nested child table, a records-path, and an empty response) and the full
suite is green. The pivot collapse is verified by a source check and is
type-checked; the on-screen behaviour over the app window is reasoned, not run
here.

