an API node is dragged *inside* an iterator -- the normal way to use it -- the
iterator runs as a container: it wraps its child nodes in a synthetic "group"
node and runs that group once per row. The API node is therefore nested in the
group's children, not a top-level node.

_flow_engine_target -- which decides the single engine a flow runs on -- only
scanned the graph's top-level nodes. The nested API node was invisible to it, so
nothing pinned the engine and the flow defaulted to SQLite, while the API node's
hidden table had been loaded into DuckDB (the default engine when DuckDB is
installed). The group's "SELECT * FROM __nbapi_..." then ran on SQLite and the
table wasn't there.

The fix makes _flow_engine_target descend into group and iterator children when
choosing the engine, applying the same logic used for top-level nodes: a nested
API node is routed to the engine the fetch actually loaded it into (the .289
change), and a nested file/input/SQL node pins the engine the same way it would
at the top level. The group now runs on the engine that holds the data, and the
body reads its table.

This does not change how any flow runs on success or how single-engine flows
behave; it only widens engine selection to see inputs nested inside containers.
The loop and ${variable} substitution were never involved -- the error already
showed the date resolving each pass.

Reasoned vs tested: covered by a new test asserting a group (and an iterator)
with a nested API node recorded as living in DuckDB routes the flow to DuckDB,
plus a fallback (a group with no engine-pinning child stays local). The
container-iterator path with a child API node is also exercised end-to-end on
SQLite in the suite; the DuckDB end-to-end run is confirmed on the real
Windows/Citrix build, where DuckDB is present.

