build 2026-06-25.289  (v2.10.18)

Iterator + API node: read the API node's data from the engine it loaded into.

An iterator (or while loop) whose body contained an API node could fail every
pass with "The group node couldn't run: OperationalError: no such table:
__nbapi_..." even though the fetch succeeded. The hidden table the API node
loads its response into is created in whichever engine is the default for new
data -- DuckDB whenever it is installed -- but the flow that reads it was being
routed to SQLite, so the body's "SELECT * FROM __nbapi_..." looked for a DuckDB
table in SQLite and reported it missing.

The cause: a flow runs on a single engine, chosen by _flow_engine_target from
its input tables. For an API node it read the engine out of the cached catalog,
and the freshly-created hidden table was not reflected there at that instant
inside an iterator pass, so the lookup came back empty and the flow defaulted to
SQLite. The data was in DuckDB the whole time.

The fix makes _flow_engine_target trust the engine the fetch actually recorded
for the node (the API-node registry tracks, per node, the engine its table and
error table live in) rather than re-deriving it from the catalog cache. When no
fetch has run for a node it still falls back to the catalog, so the manual
(non-iterator) path is unchanged. This routes the flow to the engine that holds
the data, and the body reads its table.

This does not change what loads on a successful fetch or how any single-engine
flow runs; it only corrects engine selection when an API node's hidden table
is not yet visible in the cache. The loop and ${variable} substitution were
never the problem -- the error already showed the date resolving.

Reasoned vs tested: covered by a new test that records an API node's table as
living in DuckDB while leaving it absent from both cached catalogs (the bug
condition) and asserts the flow targets DuckDB, plus a fallback case (an
un-fetched node still resolves to the local engine). The end-to-end iterator +
API-node-on-DuckDB path itself is exercised on the real Windows/Citrix build,
where DuckDB is present.

