build 2026-06-25.221

Stall / "failed to fetch" cascade -- audit + hardening
-------------------------------------------------------
Full review of how a stuck or failed SQLite/DuckDB operation impacts later
loads and table-creations, plus fixes so one wedged operation can no longer
take the whole app down.

* Deadline-bounded engine lock. Every engine touches its connection under a
  single write lock. Previously a foreground operation (create-table, load,
  query, export) would wait on that lock FOREVER if another operation was
  stuck -- a wedged on-disk DuckDB call, a slow checkpoint, or the startup
  restore replaying earlier loads. The waiting worker threads piled up and
  never returned, which the UI surfaced as a frozen spinner and then the
  opaque "failed to fetch". The connection lock is now deadline-bounded: a
  foreground op waits at most ~30s for the engine and then fails fast with a
  clear, retryable "engine is busy / may be stuck -- retry or restart"
  message instead of hanging. This bounds only the WAIT to acquire the lock,
  never a running operation -- a legitimately long load/query that already
  holds the lock still runs to completion; only operations queued behind it
  are bounded. Re-entrancy and the non-blocking acquire used by the
  background checkpoint are preserved.

* Malformed / oversized uploads no longer drop the connection. The
  multipart/form-data parse ran outside the request handler's error guard,
  so a bad upload body could close the socket with no response -- another
  source of "failed to fetch" when loading data. It now returns a clean
  HTTP 400 and the server stays responsive.

Net effect: a failed or stuck load/query can no longer cascade into
indefinitely-stalled table creations and loads. Worst case is now a prompt,
clear error rather than a hang. (Note: the underlying cause of a DuckDB call
wedging on a slow/locked on-disk path is environmental and can't be
reproduced here -- this change prevents the cascade and the dead-app state
it caused.)
