build 2026-06-20.120
  Temp directories no longer accumulate across runs.

  Every temp artifact SamQL makes -- the DuckDB on-disk database and its spill
  directory, per-result row stores, Parquet result temporaries, export files,
  and JSON-flatten spill directories -- already lives under one per-process
  directory (<system-temp>/samql/<pid>/) and is removed promptly: row stores are
  deleted when a result is evicted or cleared, Parquet and export temporaries are
  unlinked right after they are written/sent, and the JSON spill directory is
  removed after each load. A clean shutdown deletes the whole instance directory,
  and startup sweeps directories left by earlier runs that were killed before
  they could clean up (their owning process is gone).

  The gap: that sweep ran only at startup, so a clean run never tidied orphans
  left by a previously-crashed run until the next launch. A graceful shutdown
  (Ctrl+C / SIGTERM / window close) now sweeps those stale directories too, so
  the temp area is tidied at both ends of every run. The sweep only removes
  directories whose owning process has exited -- a concurrently running instance
  is never touched.

  Tests: 213 (backend 154, http 40, frontend 19). New: the shutdown handler both
  removes this instance's temp directory and sweeps stale ones from prior runs.

  Sandbox note: deletion of an open file while it is still locked is a
