build 2026-06-20.100
  Two query optimisations for big flows -- projection pushdown and shared-
  subgraph materialisation. Backend-only logic; no new dependencies.

  Projection pushdown (column pruning):
    - Source nodes (input / directory / append-from-folder) now read only the
      columns used downstream, so a wide table behind a Select isn't fully
      scanned and intermediate temp tables carry fewer columns.
    - A backward column-liveness pass walks the flow from the materialised
      target back to the sources. It is conservative: a Select drives pruning
      (as does a chain of Filter / Sort / Dedupe / Unique above one), while
      joins, formulas, aggregates and rename-columns are treated as "needs
      everything", so pruning only happens where it is provably safe.
    - Sound by construction: an unused output port (e.g. a Filter's unwired
      false branch) contributes nothing; a filter's referenced columns always
      survive even when dropped from the output; and the source intersects the
      wanted set against its real columns case-insensitively.
    - Applies to every run / preview / export path. Toggle off with the
      project_pushdown config flag if ever needed.

  Shared-subgraph materialisation:
    - Run all now exports its file-output nodes in one shared pass, so a
      subgraph feeding more than one output is computed once for the batch
      instead of once per output. Write / chart / dashboard terminals keep
      their per-terminal path; a shared-build failure falls back to exporting
      each node on its own so errors still localise.
    - New backend: _materialize_flows builds several targets sharing one temp
      cache; export_nodeflow_many + POST /api/nodeflow/export-many stream each
      output from its own temp (with same-name de-collision).

  Tests: 195 in the bundled suite (was 191) -- pushdown liveness + correctness
  + soundness, pushdown oddities (spaced / keyword / unicode / function-like
  names, case, string literals), shared-subgraph "computed once" + cycle
  detection, the export-many endpoint, and the run-all wiring.

