  Nodebook: node fusion -- fewer temp tables, the engine optimises across steps.

  A flow used to write one temp table per node: a chain of five nodes meant
  five CREATE TEMP TABLE passes, each fully materialised before the next read
  it. Fusion collapses a run of SQL-only, single-consumer nodes into one nested
  query, so the database planner optimises the whole run (pushing filters down,
  dropping unused columns) and far fewer temp tables are written. Results are
  identical -- only the number of intermediate temp tables changes.

  Boundaries (still materialised, as a shared temp table):
  - a pivot -- its columns are shaped at run time, and it reads its input twice;
  - a node whose output feeds more than one consumer -- computed once and
    shared, never re-inlined (so nothing is recomputed and a random/sample node
    stays consistent across its consumers);
  - a SQL node -- its {{in}} token may appear more than once, so its input is
    materialised rather than duplicated into the query;
  - multi-input nodes (join, union) end each fused run at their inputs;
  - the flow's target itself.

  Safety: if a fused query hits an execution error, the whole flow is rebuilt
  node-by-node automatically, so the failure is attributed to a single node and
  behaviour never regresses versus the old path. Fusion is on by default and can
  be turned off with the fuse_flows config flag.

  Measured (SQLite, in-sandbox): a 4-node linear chain went from 4 temp tables
  to 1; a diamond (one node feeding two branches) from 4 to 2, with the shared
  node materialised exactly once -- all with byte-identical results.

  Tests: fused vs node-by-node equivalence on a linear chain, a diamond, and a
  SQL node whose {{in}} appears twice, plus the temp-count drop (4->1 linear,
  shared-node-once on the diamond). Full suite: 143 passed / 12 skipped.
  (Measured live on SQLite; DuckDB isn't in the sandbox, though the same nested
  SQL runs there and the per-node fallback makes a composition surprise safe.)

