  Second audit pass -- REST-loader hardening; the rest held up.

  Re-audited the back end and the new Nodebook code (SQL / write nodes,
  undo/redo, minimap) for breakage, stalls, leaks, and perf. Findings:

  - REST (URL) loader is now restricted to http(s) and size-capped. It used
    urllib directly, which also accepts file:// and other schemes, so the
    "HTTP(S) endpoint" loader could be pointed at a local file or a non-web
    address; it now refuses anything but http:// / https://. It also read the
    whole response with no limit, so a huge or hostile endpoint could exhaust
    memory; the read is now capped (512 MB) with a clear "too large -- download
    it and load the file instead" message.

  Verified healthy (no change needed):
  - Undo/redo is sound -- node, position, and config edits are all immutable
    updates ({...n, config:{...}}), so history snapshots never share mutable
    state; history is bounded (80 steps) and the watcher coalesces a burst
    (drag / typing) into one step.
  - The minimap recompute is O(nodes) per render (cheap), its resize listener
    is cleaned up, and it only mounts while the Nodebook view is active.
  - The SQL node's column probe routes to the right engine (DuckDB vs SQLite)
    in both source and {{in}}-transform modes, via the table-name-based engine
    chooser; wrapping the user query as a subquery makes multi-statement or
    non-SELECT input fail safely.
  - Result paging (DiskBackedRows) is SQLite-backed with on-demand indexing and
    guarded by an RLock with check_same_thread=False, so concurrent paging from
    the threaded server is safe; the canvas drag listeners use stable ([]) deps.

  Tests: the REST loader refuses file:// / ftp:// / bare-path / gopher:// and
    lets an https URL past the scheme guard. Full suite: 142 passed / 12
    skipped.

