build 2026-06-20.60
  Codebase audit -- three correctness/robustness fixes; no behaviour change for
  normal use.

  Audited the back end for functions that break others, stalls, memory leaks,
  performance traps, and latent bugs. The structure held up well -- bounded
  result cache with closed-on-evict temp files, per-PID temp dirs that are
  swept at startup (so even a crash can't leak them), debounced background
  cleanup, cycle guards on the Nodebook graph walks, a row-count-gated /
  column-selective auto-indexer, and SQL-Server cursors closed in finally with
  a single-pass catalog query. Three concrete issues were found and fixed:

  - Statement splitter ignored block comments. A ';' inside a /* ... */ comment
    would wrongly split one statement into several (it already handled ';'
    inside strings and -- line comments). Now block comments are skipped too.
  - A free-text table name could create an un-droppable table. The Nodebook
    create-table node names its table from the (free-text) label; a name with a
    double-quote produced a table that later code -- which refers to it as
    "<name>" -- couldn't drop or count. Create-table names are now reduced to a
    safe identifier (and a digit-leading name is prefixed).
  - drop_table didn't escape the identifier. As defence-in-depth (e.g. a
    quote-named table created by raw SQL), DROP TABLE / DROP VIEW now quote the
    name properly on both SQLite and DuckDB, so any table can be dropped without
    a SQL error. (For ordinary names the generated SQL is unchanged.)

  Flagged for review (not changed): on DuckDB, execute() holds the connection
  lock against a concurrent CHECKPOINT but execute_cursor() does not -- it uses
  an independent .cursor(), which is the intended thread-safe pattern, but the
  asymmetry is worth a deliberate check on a machine with DuckDB installed
  (it can't be exercised in this sandbox).

  Tests: the statement splitter (';' in string / line comment / block comment),
  create-table name sanitisation + that the result is droppable, and dropping a
  quote-named table without error. Full suite: 137 passed / 12 skipped.

